# 📓 SOC Notes — Day Log (DNS, C2, HTTPS)

## 🧠 1. DNS Beaconing (C2 Communication)

### What it is
- Malware uses DNS to communicate with attacker (C2 server)
- Happens at regular intervals (e.g., every 5s, 10s, 60s)

### Key Indicators
- High-frequency DNS queries
- Random-looking domains (DGA-like)
- Same destination IP repeatedly
- Consistent timing pattern

### Logs to Check
- DNS query logs
- Firewall outbound logs
- EDR network telemetry


---

## 🧠 2. DoS vs Beaconing

### DoS (Denial of Service)
- Goal: Overwhelm a target
- High traffic volume
- Irregular/chaotic pattern

### Beaconing
- Goal: Maintain communication with C2
- Low, consistent traffic
- Regular timing pattern

> ⚠️ Key Difference: Behavior pattern, not just traffic volume


---

## 🧠 3. Attack Flow (Kill Chain Thinking)

1. Initial Access → Phishing email (PDF)
2. Execution → Malicious code runs
3. Command & Control → System starts beaconing

> Always identify: “Which stage am I seeing?”


